{"title_page": "Moonage Daydream", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Moonage Daydream\n| cover      = Moonage Daydream by The Arnold Corns UK vinyl 1971.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = A-side label to the 1971 UK single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Arnold Corns]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Hang On to Yourself]]\n| released   = May 1971\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 25 February 1971\n| studio     = [[Radio Luxembourg]], London\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:52\n| label      = [[B&C Records|B&C]]\n| writer     = [[David Bowie]]\n| producer   = David Bowie\n| chronology = [[Arnold Corns]]\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = 1971\n| next_title = [[Hang On to Yourself]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n{{Infobox song \n| name           = Moonage Daydream\n| artist         = [[David Bowie]]\n| album          = [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]\n| released       = 16 June 1972\n| recorded       = 12 November 1971\n| studio         = [[Trident Studios|Trident]], London\n| genre          = [[Glam rock]]\n| length         = {{duration|m=4|s=37}}\n| writer         = David Bowie\n| label          = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer       = \n*David Bowie\n*[[Ken Scott]]\n| tracks         = {{The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars tracks}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Moonage Daydream'''\" is a song by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]]. It was originally recorded in February 1971 at [[Radio Luxembourg]]'s studios in London and released as a single by his short-lived band [[Arnold Corns]] in May 1971 on [[B&C Records]]. Bowie subsequently re-recorded the song later that year with his backing band [[the Spiders from Mars]]\u2014comprising [[Mick Ronson]], [[Trevor Bolder]] and [[Mick Woodmansey]]\u2014for release on his 1972 album ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''. The re-recording was co-produced by [[Ken Scott]] and recorded at [[Trident Studios]] in London in November 1971. On the album, the song directly introduces the character Ziggy Stardust, who describes himself as a [[Bisexuality|bisexual]] alien rock superstar who will save the Earth from the impending disaster described in the opening track \"[[Five Years (David Bowie song)|Five Years]]\". It features saxophone played by Bowie and a guitar solo and string arrangement by Ronson.\n\nSince its release, \"Moonage Daydream\" has received critical acclaim, with many deeming Ronson's guitar work its clear standout. Bolder, Woodmansey and Scott have called it the best song on the album; retrospectively, it has been named one of Bowie's greatest songs. He played it in concert throughout 1972\u201373 and on later tours. The ''Ziggy'' recording has since appeared on multiple [[compilation album]]s and in the 2014 film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'', while the Arnold Corns' recording has appeared on reissues of ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' (1970) and ''Ziggy Stardust''. The ''Ziggy'' recording has been remastered multiple times, including in 2012, which was subsequently included as part of the ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' box set in 2015, along with the Arnold Corns' recording.\n\n==Composition and recording==\n\"Moonage Daydream\" was written during Bowie's US promotional tour in early February 1971.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} After the tour Bowie formed a short-lived band, [[Arnold Corns]], named after the [[Pink Floyd]] song \"[[Arnold Layne]]\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}} Led by Bowie, the band consisted of guitarist Mark Carr-Pritchard, bassist Peter DeSomogyi and drummer Tim Broadbent, who were known previously as a trio called Rungk.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}} Arnold Corns recorded \"Moonage Daydream\" and \"[[Hang On to Yourself]]\" on 25&nbsp;February 1971 at [[Radio Luxembourg]]'s studios in London.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=206\u2013207}}{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}} Bowie later hired openly gay dress designer Freddie Burretti, for whom he wrote \"Moonage Daydream\".{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=207}} Burretti did not appear on either track's recording.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=207}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=605}} Biographer [[Peter Doggett]] writes, the original version had a \"playful science-fiction-inspired chorus, two nondescript verses with a single memorable line, and an arrangement that not only racked his voice like a martyr under the Inquisition but virtually defined the word 'shambolic'.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} According to biographer [[Nicholas Pegg]], the Corns' version lacks  the \"lightness of touch\" of the second.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} Like Doggett, Pegg criticises the recording's arrangement and Bowie's vocal, calling it a \"strained attempt\" at an American [[Rock and roll|rock'n'roll]] vocal, along with an additional \"come on, you mothers!\" lyric.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} According to [[Marc Spitz]], the Corns' version is melodically the same as the ''Ziggy'' version, but with a slightly different chorus.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}} Doggett believes that had the track and \"Hang On to Yourself\" not been re-recorded for ''Ziggy Stardust'', they would have been forgotten.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Author Kevin Cann writes that once the lyrics were revised and \"given the Ziggy treatment\", it became a \"glittering glam gem\" in the context of the album.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=253}}\n\nBowie re-recorded \"Moonage Daydream\" on 12&nbsp;November 1971 at [[Trident Studios]] in London for inclusion on ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}{{sfn|Woodmansey|2017|pp=88, 114}} Co-produced by [[Ken Scott]], the lineup consisted of Bowie's backing band known as [[the Spiders from Mars]]\u2014comprising guitarist [[Mick Ronson]], bassist [[Trevor Bolder]] and drummer [[Mick Woodmansey]].<ref name=\"Erlewine AllMusic\" /> The group recorded the track in two takes, as well as \"[[Soul Love (David Bowie song)|Soul Love]]\", \"[[Lady Stardust]]\" and a re-recording of ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' track \"[[The Supermen]]\" during the session.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=231}} The re-recording, like its parent album, is a [[glam rock]] song<ref>{{cite web|title=Masterpiece Reviews: \"David Bowie \u2013 The Rise And Fall Of Ziggy Stardust And The Spiders From Mars\"|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/video/masterpiece-reviews-david-bowie-the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|first=Sami|last=Jarroush|date=8 July 2014|accessdate=17 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918064055/https://consequenceofsound.net/video/masterpiece-reviews-david-bowie-the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars/|archivedate=18 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Perone|2007|p=32}} that uses melodic and harmonic hooks, as well as percussion and guitar influenced by [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]].{{sfn|Perone|2007|p=28}} Doggett writes that after learning from the \"vocal agonies\" of the Corns' recording, the Spiders decided to record the song three semitones lower than before.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}} Ronson begins it on guitar with a D chord described as an \"avalanche\",{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=187}} a \"pile-driver\", and an \"opening thunderbolt\" that is Ronson's \"declaration of intent\".{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}} Pegg writes that the chord \"cuts across the fade-out\" of \"[[Soul Love (David Bowie song)|Soul Love]]\" taking the listener \"into the morass of sleazy sex and surreal science fiction that occupies the album's heart.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} After a short pause, Bowie begins his vocal, which Doggett believes sounds far better than the \"metallic rasp\" of his 1970 recordings.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}} Bowie plays a saxophone and a [[pennywhistle]] during Ronson's solo, which are inspired by [[the Hollywood Argyles]]' 1960 song \"Sho Know a Lot About Love\";{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Bowie recalled in 2003 that he thought the combination of sax and piccolo was \"a great thing to put in a rock song\".<ref name=\"NME\" /> Ronson's guitar solo was mostly improvised after Bowie had conveyed the mood he wanted to him.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Bowie later recalled in his 2002 book ''Moonage Daydream'':\n\n{{block quote|[I would] literally draw out on paper with a crayon or felt-tip pen the shape of a solo. The one in 'Moonage Daydream', for instance, started as a flat line that became a fat megaphone type shape, and ended as sprays of disassociated and broken lines. I'd read somewhere that [[Frank Zappa]] used a series of drawn symbols to explain to his musicians how he wanted the shape of a composition to sound. Mick could take something like that and actually bloody play it, bring it to life. Very impressive.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}}}}\n\nThe song's strings, arranged and orchestrated by Ronson,{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} appear at the return of the chorus, climaxing in a \"steep pizzicato descent.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}} They appear again during the fadeout, this time having a \"swirling phased\" effect that was Scott's idea during the mixing stage.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Doggett writes, \"Only in the final moments did Ronson's guitar provide the climactic release that the daydream demanded, continually returning to the same motifs as if in ecstatic spasm.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}}\n\n==Lyrics==\nAs the third track on the album, \"Moonage Daydream\" directly introduces the character of Ziggy Stardust,{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} following \"[[Five Years (David Bowie song)|Five Years]]\" which describes an impending disaster that will result in Earth only having five years left and \"[[Soul Love (David Bowie song)|Soul Love]]\" in which numerous characters deal with love before the impending disaster.<ref>{{harvnb|Spitz|2009|p=187: \"Five Years\"}}; {{harvnb|Pegg|2016|p=445; \"Soul Love\"}}</ref> Once introduced, Ziggy proclaims himself \"an exotic hybrid of rock's past and mankind's future\": \"an alligator\" (strong and remorseless), \"a mama-papa\" (non-gender specific), \"the space invader\" (alien and phallic), \"a rock'n'rollin' bitch\" and a \"pink-monkey-bird\" (gay slang for a recipient of anal sex).{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Ziggy also praises the virtues of \"the church of man, love\" (or heard as \"the church of man-love\"); Pegg believes that this line is inspired in part by the proposed \"Church of God, Love and Man\" by philosopher [[Thomas Paine]], who Bowie often referenced indirectly (and directly on the 1990 [[Adrian Belew]] collaboration \"Pretty Pink Rose\").{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} Doggett believes that the \"carefree\" imagery Ziggy presents heightens the \"erotic fantasy\" of the chorus, described as \"a wet dream that was 'moonage' for the era of the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] missions\" and for the tradition of \"muse poetry\" by [[Robert Graves]], which is linked to \"ancient cults that worshipped the moon, accessing the imagination without involving the intellect.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Doggett continues that as philosopher [[Colin Wilson]] said in 1971, \"the moon goddess was the goddess of magic, of the subconscious, of poetic inspiration.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Hence, a \"moonage daydream\" might represent \"an ecstatic, instinctive path to creativity\", or nothing more than an homage to \"[[Marc Bolan]]'s brand of lyrical imagery.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Bowie used several Americanisms on the original version of the song, most of which he which retained on the re-recording, using abbreviations such as \"comin'\", \"'lectric\" and \"rock'n'rollin'\", as well as phrases such as \"busting up my brains\", \"lay the real thing on me\", \"freak out\" and \"far out\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} According to Pegg, there are several homages present\u2014including one to [[Iggy Pop]], whose lyric \"she got a TV eye on me\" turns into \"keep your 'lectric eye on me\", and one to [[Legendary Stardust Cowboy]], whose lyric \"I shot my space gun\" turns into \"put your ray gun to my head\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}\n\n==Release and reception==\n[[File:Mick Ronson 1979.jpg|thumb|180px|alt=Mick Ronson playing guitar|[[Mick Ronson]]'s guitar work received unanimous praise from music critics, with most calling it the best aspect of the track.]]\nThe original version of \"Moonage Daydream\" by the short-lived band Arnold Corns was released in the UK by [[B&C Records]] as a 7-inch single<ref name=\"Rhino\" /> with \"Hang On to Yourself\" as the B-side in May 1971.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=216}}<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Moonage Daydream\"''|others=[[Arnold Corns|The Arnold Corns]]|year=1971|publisher=[[B&C Records]]|location=UK|type=Single liner notes|id=CB 149}}</ref> The re-recorded version was released as the third track on Bowie's fifth studio album ''The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars'', between \"Soul Love\" and \"[[Starman (song)|Starman]]\", on 16&nbsp;June 1972 by [[RCA Records]].<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1972|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=SF 8287}}</ref> Discussing the song's placement in the album's track-listing, Pegg describes it as its \"keystone\" if one identifies the opening and closing tracks (\"Five Years\" and \"[[Rock 'n' Roll Suicide]]\", respectively) as the album's framework.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}\n\n{{quote box|quote=When I walked into the control room and heard \"Moonage Daydream\" played back through the speakers for the first time I knew then we really had something special. I'll never forget it.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=253}}|source= \u2013 [[Trevor Bolder]], 1993|width=20%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}\nSince its release, \"Moonage Daydream\" has received critical acclaim, with many deeming Ronson's guitar work as the clear standout. It has been called the best song on the album by Trevor Bolder, Woody Woodmansey and Ken Scott.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} In his book ''The Complete David Bowie'', Nicholas Pegg praises Ronson's guitar solo, calling it \"spectacular\" and a \"vital ingredient\" to the recording.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} He describes it as arguably Ronson's finest on a Bowie recording and renowned among guitarists as an \"all-time classic.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Reviewing the album for its 40th&nbsp;anniversary, Jordan Blum of ''[[PopMatters]]'' describes \"Moonage DayDream\", \"Hang On to Yourself\" and \"It Ain't Easy\" as \"invigorating rockers\" that are highlighted by Ronson's \"electrifying timbres.\"<ref name=\"Blum\">{{cite magazine|last=Blum|first=Jordan|date=12 July 2012|title=David Bowie \u2013 The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/160406-david-bowie-the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101090527/http://www.popmatters.com/review/160406-david-bowie-the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from|archivedate=1 January 2017|accessdate=8 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following [[Death of David Bowie|Bowie's death]] in 2016, ''Rolling Stone'' listed \"Moonage Daydream\" as one of his 30&nbsp;essential songs, giving unanimous praise to Ronson's guitar work, calling it some of the most \"jaw-dropping\" of his career.<ref name=\"RS 30 essentials\">{{cite web |author1=''Rolling Stone'' Staff |title=David Bowie: 30 Essential Songs |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/david-bowie-30-essential-songs-33438/modern-love-1983-2-152622/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=25 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203085329/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/david-bowie-30-essential-songs-33438/modern-love-1983-2-152622/ |archivedate=3 December 2019 |date=11 January 2016}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] praises Ronson's guitar work, writing \"[Ronson] plays with a maverick flair that invigorates rockers like \"[[Suffragette City]]\", \"Moonage Daydream\" and \"Hang On to Yourself\".\"<ref name=\"Erlewine AllMusic\">{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-rise-and-all-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-mw0000626129 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310010804/https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-rise-and-all-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-mw0000626129 |archivedate=10 March 2020}}</ref> Ned Raggett, also of AllMusic, calls the track one of Bowie's \"fiercest rockers ever\".<ref name=\"AllMusic Raggett\" /> He continues, \"As a prototype of glam rock's still-influential formula \u2013 descending, slow chords; high singing; sexually charged if not exploded imagery; thick, fat feedback; and more \u2013it nails it on every level.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic Raggett\" /> He finishes his review writing: \"Ronson's keyboards and final, swirling string arrangement, matched with a brilliant guitar solo, prove the icing on the cake, sealing \"Moonage Daydream\" forever as a rock classic.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic Raggett\">{{cite web |last1=Raggett |first1=Ned |title=\"Moonage Daydream\" \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/moonage-daydream-mt0044072047 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704103837/https://www.allmusic.com/song/moonage-daydream-mt0044072047 |archive-date=4 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Ultimate Classic Rock'', in their list of Bowie's ten best songs, listed \"Moonage Daydream\" at number three, calling it one of the most powerful songs on the album\u2014and of his career.<ref name=\"UCR best of\" /> They praised the lyrics and Ronson's guitar work, calling it a \"rock'n'roll tour de force.\"<ref name=\"UCR best of\">{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Spencer |title=Top 10 David Bowie songs |url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/top-david-bowie-songs/ |website=[[Ultimate Classic Rock]] |accessdate=25 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231194433/http://ultimateclassicrock.com/top-david-bowie-songs/ |archivedate=31 December 2019 |date=11 January 2016}}</ref> Ian Fortnam of ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'', when ranking every track on the album from worst to best, placed the song at number six, and praised Ronson's guitar work, calling his ending guitar solo \"\u00fcberglamtastic\" and \"to die for.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/every-track-on-david-bowies-ziggy-stardust-ranked-from-worst-to-best | title=Every song on David Bowie's Ziggy Stardust ranked from worst to best | work=Louder | first=Ian | last=Fortnam | date=11 November 2016 | accessdate=26 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826071416/https://www.loudersound.com/features/every-track-on-david-bowies-ziggy-stardust-ranked-from-worst-to-best | archive-date=26 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, ''[[NME]]'' listed the song as Bowie's 11th greatest.<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last1=Barker |first1=Emily |title=David Bowie's 40 greatest songs \u2013 as decided by ''NME'' and friends |url=https://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends-1418012 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=16 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103063248/https://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends-1418012 |archivedate=3 November 2019 |date=8 January 2018}}</ref> Alexis Petridis of ''[[The Guardian]]'' ranked \"Moonage Daydream\" 33rd in her list of Bowie's 50 greatest songs, calling Ronson's guitar solo \"mind-blowing\" and describing it as the best example of \"high-drama rock anthemics\" on ''Ziggy Stardust''.<ref name=\"Petridis Guardian\">{{cite web |last1=Petridis |first1=Alexis |title=David Bowie's 50 greatest songs \u2013 ranked! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/david-bowie-50-greatest-songs-ranked |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322224635/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/david-bowie-50-greatest-songs-ranked |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Tim Wheeler]] of the Northern Irish rock band [[Ash (band)|Ash]], in an interview with ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine, said, \"With Bowie, you're spoilt for choice when it comes to [[Science fiction|sci-fi]]-inspired songs. But 'Moonage Daydream' is my favourite. It's got a great [[Ostinato|riff]] and it sounds really pretty in a weird kind of way, even though the lyrics are quite dark.\"<ref>{{cite journal|first=Tim |last=[[Tim Wheeler|Wheeler]] |title=Sci-fi rocks |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |date=August 2007 |page=117}}</ref>\n\n==Live versions==\nBowie performed \"Moonage Daydream\" throughout 1972\u201373 on the [[Ziggy Stardust Tour]], where he would occasionally introduce it as \"a song written by Ziggy\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} A live version from the tour, recorded at Santa Monica Civic Auditorium on 20 October 1972, was released on ''[[Live Santa Monica '72]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thornton |first1=Anthony |title=David Bowie \u2013 'Live: Santa Monica '72' review |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews-david-bowie-9770-308284 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=1 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004181122/http://www.nme.com/reviews/david-bowie/9770 |archive-date=4 October 2012}}</ref> It was also performed during the tour's final concert at the [[Hammersmith Odeon]], London on 3 July 1973, where Bowie announced: \"This is the last show we'll ever do.\" This was later understood as the retiring of Ziggy Stardust.{{sfn|Buckley|1999|p=191}} This recording was released on ''[[Ziggy Stardust: The Motion Picture]]'' (1983).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Joe |first1=Viglione |title=''Ziggy Stardust: The Motion Picture'' |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-the-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000691870 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424115511/https://www.allmusic.com/album/ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-the-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000691870 |archive-date=24 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He recorded the song for the [[BBC]] radio programme ''[[Sounds of the Seventies|Sounds of the 70s]]: [[John Peel]]'' on 16 May 1972. This recording was later released on the album ''[[Bowie at the Beeb]]'' in 2000.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Bowie at the Beeb: The Best of the BBC Radio Sessions 68\u201372'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/bowie-at-the-beeb-the-best-of-the-bbc-radio-sessions-bonus-disc-mw0000619751 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702122107/https://www.allmusic.com/album/bowie-at-the-beeb-the-best-of-the-bbc-radio-sessions-bonus-disc-mw0000619751 |archive-date=2 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bowie subsequently performed the track on the [[Diamond Dogs Tour]], and on the [[Outside Tour|Outside]], [[Earthling Tour|Earthling]] and [[Heathen Tour|Heathen]] tours.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Recordings from the Diamond Dogs Tour have been released on ''[[David Live]]'' (1974) and ''[[Cracked Actor (Live Los Angeles '74)]]'' (2017).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''David Live'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/david-live-mw0000033632 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424115457/https://www.allmusic.com/album/david-live-mw0000033632 |archive-date=24 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Randle |first1=Chris |title=David Bowie: ''Cracked Actor (Live Los Angeles '74)'' |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-cracked-actor-live-los-angeles-74/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=29 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117144718/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-cracked-actor-live-los-angeles-74/ |archive-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A live version from the Outside tour, recorded on 13 December 1995, was released on the \"[[Hallo Spaceboy]]\" single in 1996.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}}\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Arnold Corns' version (without the spoken intro \"Whenever you're ready\") was released as a bonus track on the 1990 [[Rykodisc]] re-release of ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' and on the 2002 reissue of ''Ziggy Stardust''.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Man Who Sold the World|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1990|publisher=[[Rykodisc]]|location=US|type=CD liner notes|id=RCD 10132}}</ref><ref name=\"rkyodisc\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=2002|publisher=[[EMI]]|location=US|type=liner notes|id=72435 39826 2}}</ref> The spoken intro was restored for release on ''Re:Call 1'', part of the ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' compilation, in 2015.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}<ref name=\"five years box set\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Five Years (1969\u20131973)|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=2015|publisher=[[Parlophone]]|location=UK, Europe & US|type=Box set liner notes|id=DBXL 1}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Ziggy Stardust'' recording has since appeared on multiple [[compilation album]]s, including the 1989 box set ''[[Sound + Vision (box set)|Sound + Vision]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Sound + Vision'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/sound-vision-mw0000653974 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508195205/https://www.allmusic.com/album/sound-vision-mw0000653974 |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Best of Bowie'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-bowie-mw0000694821 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401192732/https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-bowie-mw0000694821 |archive-date=1 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Nothing Has Changed]]'' (2014),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Nothing Has Changed'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/nothing-has-changed-mw0002764063 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508195204/https://www.allmusic.com/album/nothing-has-changed-mw0002764063 |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ''[[Legacy (The Very Best of David Bowie)|Legacy]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Legacy'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/legacy-mw0002986167 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508195207/https://www.allmusic.com/album/legacy-mw0002986167 |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ''Ziggy'' recording, along with its parent album, has been remastered multiple times, including in 1990 by [[Rykodisc]],<ref>{{cite web|title=The Rise & Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars [Bonus Tracks]|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/the-rise-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-bonus-tracks-mr0001727546|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002175230/http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/the-rise-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-bonus-tracks-mr0001727546|archivedate=2 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1990|publisher=[[Rykodisc]]|location=US|type=liner notes|id=RCD 10134}}</ref> and in 2012 for its 40th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=2012|publisher=[[EMI]]|location=Europe|type=liner notes|id=5099946361417}}</ref> The 2012 remaster and the 2003 remixes by producer Ken Scott, along with the original Arnold Corns' recording, were included on the box set ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' in 2015.<ref name=\"five years box set\" /> A new mix of the track also appears on the 2002 reissue of ''Ziggy Stardust'', on which, in Cann's words, Ronson's guitar is \"to the fore.\"<ref name=\"rkyodisc\" />{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=255}} This mix was originally featured in a 1998 [[Dunlop Tyres|Dunlop]] television commercial.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}}<ref name=\"Drake Metrotimes\">{{cite web|last=Drake|first=Rossiter|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars: 30th Anniversary Edition|url=https://www.metrotimes.com/city-slang/archives/2002/09/04/the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-30th-anniversary-edition|work=[[Metro Times]]|date=4 September 2002|accessdate=2 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002175230/https://www.metrotimes.com/city-slang/archives/2002/09/04/the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-30th-anniversary-edition|archivedate=2 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in the 2014 film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' and on its [[Guardians of the Galaxy: Awesome Mix Vol. 1 (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)|soundtrack]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=329}}<ref name=\"Vulture Guardians\">{{cite web|url=https://vulture.com/2014/08/how-guardians-of-the-galaxy-music-soundtrack-was-chosen.html |title=Director James Gunn on How He Chose the Music in Guardians of the Galaxy |last=Suskind |first=Alex |work=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]] |date=August 8, 2014 |accessdate=September 19, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ShD2pm91?url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/08/how-guardians-of-the-galaxy-music-soundtrack-was-chosen.html |archivedate=September 19, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is heard in the film during the [[Guardians of the Galaxy (2008 team)|Guardians]]' entrance to [[Knowhere]], the headquarters of the [[Collector (comics)|Collector]].<ref name=\"Vulture Guardians\" /> Of all the songs on the soundtrack, \"Moonage Daydream\" was the only song added in post-production.<ref name=\"Vulture Guardians\" /> Director [[James Gunn]] was unsure about using it initially, but ended up choosing it over \"[[Wichita Lineman]]\" by [[Glen Campbell]] and \"[[Mama Told Me Not to Come|Mama Told Me (Not to Come)]]\" by [[Three Dog Night]].<ref name=\"Vulture Guardians\" />\n\n''Moonage Daydream: The Life and Times of Ziggy Stardust'', a book written by Bowie, is named after the song and was published in 2002 by [[Genesis Publications]]. It documents the years 1972\u201373 and is fully illustrated with the photography of [[Mick Rock]]. Bowie met him in 1972 and they formed a working relationship and lasting friendship. Rock was the only photographer authorised to record the two-year career of [[David Bowie#Ziggy Stardust|Ziggy Stardust]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Moonage Daydream: The Life & Times of Ziggy Stardust |url=https://www.amazon.com/Moonage-Daydream-Times-Ziggy-Stardust/dp/0789313502 |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219182607/https://www.amazon.com/Moonage-Daydream-Times-Ziggy-Stardust/dp/0789313502 |archive-date=19 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Genesis Publications \u2013 ''Moonage Daydream'' |url=https://www.genesis-publications.com/book/0904351866/moonage-daydream |publisher=[[Genesis Publications]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216074038/https://www.genesis-publications.com/book/0904351866/moonage-daydream |archive-date=16 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Arnold Corns version\nPersonnel per Kevin Cann and Nicholas Pegg.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=206\u2013207}}\n* David Bowie{{spaced ndash}} vocals, rhythm guitar, producer\n* Freddie Burretti{{spaced ndash}} vocals (credited)<ref name=\"Rhino\">{{cite web |title=Single Stories: David Bowie, \"Moonage Daydream\" |url=https://www.rhino.com/article/single-stories-david-bowie-moonage-daydream |publisher=Rhino |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=7 May 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310010927/https://www.rhino.com/article/single-stories-david-bowie-moonage-daydream |archivedate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Mark Carr-Pritchard{{spaced ndash}} guitar\n* Peter DeSomogyi{{spaced ndash}} bass\n* Tim Broadbent{{spaced ndash}} drums, tambourine\n{{col-2}}\n;''Ziggy Stardust'' version\nPersonnel per Kevin Cann and Nicholas Pegg.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=252}}\n* David Bowie{{spaced ndash}} lead vocals, acoustic guitar, [[saxophone]], [[pennywhistle]], producer\n* [[Mick Ronson]]{{spaced ndash}} electric guitar, piano, backing vocals, [[string section|string]] arrangements\n* [[Trevor Bolder]]{{spaced ndash}} bass\n* [[Mick Woodmansey|Mick \"Woody\" Woodmansey]]{{spaced ndash}} drums\n* [[Ken Scott]]{{spaced ndash}} producer\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book|last=Buckley |first=David |year=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |isbn=978-1-85227-784-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cann |first=Kevin |year=2010 |title=Any Day Now \u2013 David Bowie: The London Years: 1947\u20131974 |publisher=Adelita |isbn=978-0-95520-177-6 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Doggett |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Doggett |year=2012 |title=The Man Who Sold the World: David Bowie and the 1970s |publisher=[[HarperCollins|HarperCollins Publishers]] |isbn=978-0-06-202466-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |publisher=Titan Books |edition=7th |location=London |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-78565-365-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Perone|first=James|title=The Words and Music of David Bowie|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|date=2007|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C6bz2BFdPawC|isbn=978-0-27-599245-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Spitz |first=Marc |author-link1=Marc Spitz |title=Bowie: A Biography |publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]] |year=2009  |isbn=978-0-307-71699-6|title-link=Bowie: A Biography |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Woodmansey|first=Woody<!--credited name-->|authorlink=Mick Woodmansey|title=Spider from Mars: My Life with Bowie|publisher=St. Martin's Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2P3hCwAAQBAJ|isbn=978-1-25-011762-5|date=2017|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|moonage-daydream}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Ken Scott]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Rock ballads]]\n[[Category:1970s ballads]]\n[[Category:Outer space themed songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Moonage Daydream\n| cover      = Moonage Daydream by The Arnold Corns UK vinyl 1971.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = A-side label to the 1971 UK single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Arnold Corns]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Hang On to Yourself]]\n| released   = May 1971\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 25 February 1971\n| studio     = [[Radio Luxembourg]], London\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:52\n| label      = [[B&C Records|B&C]]\n| writer     = [[David Bowie]]\n| producer   = David Bowie\n| chronology = [[Arnold Corns]]\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = 1971\n| next_title = [[Hang On to Yourself]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n{{Infobox song \n| name           = Moonage Daydream\n| artist         = [[David Bowie]]\n| album          = [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]\n| released       = 16 June 1972\n| recorded       = 12 November 1971\n| studio         = [[Trident Studios|Trident]], London\n| genre          = [[Glam rock]]\n| length         = {{duration|m=4|s=37}}\n| writer         = David Bowie\n| label          = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer       = \n*David Bowie\n*[[Ken Scott]]\n| tracks         = {{The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars tracks}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Moonage Daydream'''\" is a song by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]]. It was originally recorded in February 1971 at [[Radio Luxembourg]]'s studios in London and released as a single by his short-lived band [[Arnold Corns]] in May 1971 on [[B&C Records]]. Bowie subsequently re-recorded the song later that year with his backing band [[the Spiders from Mars]]\u2014comprising [[Mick Ronson]], [[Trevor Bolder]] and [[Mick Woodmansey]]\u2014for release on his 1972 album ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''. The re-recording was co-produced by [[Ken Scott]] and recorded at [[Trident Studios]] in London in November 1971. On the album, the song directly introduces the character Ziggy Stardust, who describes himself as a [[Bisexuality|bisexual]] alien rock superstar who will save the Earth from the impending disaster described in the opening track \"[[Five Years (David Bowie song)|Five Years]]\". It features saxophone played by Bowie and a guitar solo and string arrangement by Ronson.\n\nSince its release, \"Moonage Daydream\" has received critical acclaim, with many deeming Ronson's guitar work its clear standout. Bolder, Woodmansey and Scott have called it the best song on the album; retrospectively, it has been named one of Bowie's greatest songs. He played it in concert throughout 1972\u201373 and on later tours. The ''Ziggy'' recording has since appeared on multiple [[compilation album]]s and in the 2014 film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'', while the Arnold Corns' recording has appeared on reissues of ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' (1970) and ''Ziggy Stardust''. The ''Ziggy'' recording has been remastered multiple times, including in 2012, which was subsequently included as part of the ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' box set in 2015, along with the Arnold Corns' recording.\n\n==Composition and recording==\n\"Moonage Daydream\" was written during Bowie's US promotional tour in early February 1971.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} After the tour Bowie formed a short-lived band, [[Arnold Corns]], named after the [[Pink Floyd]] song \"[[Arnold Layne]]\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}} Led by Bowie, the band consisted of guitarist Mark Carr-Pritchard, bassist Peter DeSomogyi and drummer Tim Broadbent, who were known previously as a trio called Rungk.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}} Arnold Corns recorded \"Moonage Daydream\" and \"[[Hang On to Yourself]]\" on 25&nbsp;February 1971 at [[Radio Luxembourg]]'s studios in London.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=206\u2013207}}{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}} Bowie later hired openly gay dress designer Freddie Burretti, for whom he wrote \"Moonage Daydream\".{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=207}} Burretti did not appear on either track's recording.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=207}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=605}} Biographer [[Peter Doggett]] writes, the original version had a \"playful science-fiction-inspired chorus, two nondescript verses with a single memorable line, and an arrangement that not only racked his voice like a martyr under the Inquisition but virtually defined the word 'shambolic'.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} According to biographer [[Nicholas Pegg]], the Corns' version lacks  the \"lightness of touch\" of the second.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} Like Doggett, Pegg criticises the recording's arrangement and Bowie's vocal, calling it a \"strained attempt\" at an American [[Rock and roll|rock'n'roll]] vocal, along with an additional \"come on, you mothers!\" lyric.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} According to [[Marc Spitz]], the Corns' version is melodically the same as the ''Ziggy'' version, but with a slightly different chorus.{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=156}} Doggett believes that had the track and \"Hang On to Yourself\" not been re-recorded for ''Ziggy Stardust'', they would have been forgotten.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Author Kevin Cann writes that once the lyrics were revised and \"given the Ziggy treatment\", it became a \"glittering glam gem\" in the context of the album.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=253}}\n\nBowie re-recorded \"Moonage Daydream\" on 12&nbsp;November 1971 at [[Trident Studios]] in London for inclusion on ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}{{sfn|Woodmansey|2017|pp=88, 114}} Co-produced by [[Ken Scott]], the lineup consisted of Bowie's backing band known as [[the Spiders from Mars]]\u2014comprising guitarist [[Mick Ronson]], bassist [[Trevor Bolder]] and drummer [[Mick Woodmansey]].<ref name=\"Erlewine AllMusic\" /> The group recorded the track in two takes, as well as \"[[Soul Love (David Bowie song)|Soul Love]]\", \"[[Lady Stardust]]\" and a re-recording of ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' track \"[[The Supermen]]\" during the session.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=231}} The re-recording, like its parent album, is a [[glam rock]] song<ref>{{cite web|title=Masterpiece Reviews: \"David Bowie \u2013 The Rise And Fall Of Ziggy Stardust And The Spiders From Mars\"|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/video/masterpiece-reviews-david-bowie-the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|first=Sami|last=Jarroush|date=8 July 2014|accessdate=17 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918064055/https://consequenceofsound.net/video/masterpiece-reviews-david-bowie-the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars/|archivedate=18 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{sfn|Perone|2007|p=32}} that uses melodic and harmonic hooks, as well as percussion and guitar influenced by [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]].{{sfn|Perone|2007|p=28}} Doggett writes that after learning from the \"vocal agonies\" of the Corns' recording, the Spiders decided to record the song three semitones lower than before.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}} Ronson begins it on guitar with a D chord described as an \"avalanche\",{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=187}} a \"pile-driver\", and an \"opening thunderbolt\" that is Ronson's \"declaration of intent\".{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}} Pegg writes that the chord \"cuts across the fade-out\" of \"[[Soul Love (David Bowie song)|Soul Love]]\" taking the listener \"into the morass of sleazy sex and surreal science fiction that occupies the album's heart.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} After a short pause, Bowie begins his vocal, which Doggett believes sounds far better than the \"metallic rasp\" of his 1970 recordings.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}} Bowie plays a saxophone and a [[pennywhistle]] during Ronson's solo, which are inspired by [[the Hollywood Argyles]]' 1960 song \"Sho Know a Lot About Love\";{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Bowie recalled in 2003 that he thought the combination of sax and piccolo was \"a great thing to put in a rock song\".<ref name=\"NME\" /> Ronson's guitar solo was mostly improvised after Bowie had conveyed the mood he wanted to him.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Bowie later recalled in his 2002 book ''Moonage Daydream'':\n\n{{block quote|[I would] literally draw out on paper with a crayon or felt-tip pen the shape of a solo. The one in 'Moonage Daydream', for instance, started as a flat line that became a fat megaphone type shape, and ended as sprays of disassociated and broken lines. I'd read somewhere that [[Frank Zappa]] used a series of drawn symbols to explain to his musicians how he wanted the shape of a composition to sound. Mick could take something like that and actually bloody play it, bring it to life. Very impressive.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}}}}\n\nThe song's strings, arranged and orchestrated by Ronson,{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} appear at the return of the chorus, climaxing in a \"steep pizzicato descent.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}} They appear again during the fadeout, this time having a \"swirling phased\" effect that was Scott's idea during the mixing stage.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Doggett writes, \"Only in the final moments did Ronson's guitar provide the climactic release that the daydream demanded, continually returning to the same motifs as if in ecstatic spasm.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=119}}\n\n==Lyrics==\nAs the third track on the album, \"Moonage Daydream\" directly introduces the character of Ziggy Stardust,{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} following \"[[Five Years (David Bowie song)|Five Years]]\" which describes an impending disaster that will result in Earth only having five years left and \"[[Soul Love (David Bowie song)|Soul Love]]\" in which numerous characters deal with love before the impending disaster.<ref>{{harvnb|Spitz|2009|p=187: \"Five Years\"}}; {{harvnb|Pegg|2016|p=445; \"Soul Love\"}}</ref> Once introduced, Ziggy proclaims himself \"an exotic hybrid of rock's past and mankind's future\": \"an alligator\" (strong and remorseless), \"a mama-papa\" (non-gender specific), \"the space invader\" (alien and phallic), \"a rock'n'rollin' bitch\" and a \"pink-monkey-bird\" (gay slang for a recipient of anal sex).{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Ziggy also praises the virtues of \"the church of man, love\" (or heard as \"the church of man-love\"); Pegg believes that this line is inspired in part by the proposed \"Church of God, Love and Man\" by philosopher [[Thomas Paine]], who Bowie often referenced indirectly (and directly on the 1990 [[Adrian Belew]] collaboration \"Pretty Pink Rose\").{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} Doggett believes that the \"carefree\" imagery Ziggy presents heightens the \"erotic fantasy\" of the chorus, described as \"a wet dream that was 'moonage' for the era of the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] missions\" and for the tradition of \"muse poetry\" by [[Robert Graves]], which is linked to \"ancient cults that worshipped the moon, accessing the imagination without involving the intellect.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Doggett continues that as philosopher [[Colin Wilson]] said in 1971, \"the moon goddess was the goddess of magic, of the subconscious, of poetic inspiration.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Hence, a \"moonage daydream\" might represent \"an ecstatic, instinctive path to creativity\", or nothing more than an homage to \"[[Marc Bolan]]'s brand of lyrical imagery.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=118}} Bowie used several Americanisms on the original version of the song, most of which he which retained on the re-recording, using abbreviations such as \"comin'\", \"'lectric\" and \"rock'n'rollin'\", as well as phrases such as \"busting up my brains\", \"lay the real thing on me\", \"freak out\" and \"far out\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} According to Pegg, there are several homages present\u2014including one to [[Iggy Pop]], whose lyric \"she got a TV eye on me\" turns into \"keep your 'lectric eye on me\", and one to [[Legendary Stardust Cowboy]], whose lyric \"I shot my space gun\" turns into \"put your ray gun to my head\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}\n\n==Release and reception==\n[[File:Mick Ronson 1979.jpg|thumb|180px|alt=Mick Ronson playing guitar|[[Mick Ronson]]'s guitar work received unanimous praise from music critics, with most calling it the best aspect of the track.]]\nThe original version of \"Moonage Daydream\" by the short-lived band Arnold Corns was released in the UK by [[B&C Records]] as a single with \"Hang On to Yourself\" as the B-side in May 1971.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=216}}<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Moonage Daydream\"''|others=[[Arnold Corns|The Arnold Corns]]|year=1971|publisher=[[B&C Records]]|location=UK|type=Single liner notes|id=CB 149}}</ref> The re-recorded version was released as the third track on Bowie's fifth studio album ''The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars'', between \"Soul Love\" and \"[[Starman (song)|Starman]]\", on 16&nbsp;June 1972 by [[RCA Records]].<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1972|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=SF 8287}}</ref> Discussing the song's placement in the album's track-listing, Pegg describes it as its \"keystone\" if one identifies the opening and closing tracks (\"Five Years\" and \"[[Rock 'n' Roll Suicide]]\", respectively) as the album's framework.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}\n\n{{quote box|quote=When I walked into the control room and heard \"Moonage Daydream\" played back through the speakers for the first time I knew then we really had something special. I'll never forget it.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=253}}|source= \u2013 [[Trevor Bolder]], 1993|width=20%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}\nSince its release, \"Moonage Daydream\" has received critical acclaim, with many deeming Ronson's guitar work as the clear standout. It has been called the best song on the album by Trevor Bolder, Woody Woodmansey and Ken Scott.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} In his book ''The Complete David Bowie'', Nicholas Pegg praises Ronson's guitar solo, calling it \"spectacular\" and a \"vital ingredient\" to the recording.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} He describes it as arguably Ronson's finest on a Bowie recording and renowned among guitarists as an \"all-time classic.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Reviewing the album for its 40th&nbsp;anniversary, Jordan Blum of ''[[PopMatters]]'' describes \"Moonage DayDream\", \"Hang On to Yourself\" and \"It Ain't Easy\" as \"invigorating rockers\" that are highlighted by Ronson's \"electrifying timbres.\"<ref name=\"Blum\">{{cite magazine|last=Blum|first=Jordan|date=12 July 2012|title=David Bowie \u2013 The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/160406-david-bowie-the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101090527/http://www.popmatters.com/review/160406-david-bowie-the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from|archivedate=1 January 2017|accessdate=8 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following [[Death of David Bowie|Bowie's death]] in 2016, ''Rolling Stone'' listed \"Moonage Daydream\" as one of his 30&nbsp;essential songs, giving unanimous praise to Ronson's guitar work, calling it some of the most \"jaw-dropping\" of his career.<ref name=\"RS 30 essentials\">{{cite web |author1=''Rolling Stone'' Staff |title=David Bowie: 30 Essential Songs |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/david-bowie-30-essential-songs-33438/modern-love-1983-2-152622/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=25 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203085329/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/david-bowie-30-essential-songs-33438/modern-love-1983-2-152622/ |archivedate=3 December 2019 |date=11 January 2016}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] praises Ronson's guitar work, writing \"[Ronson] plays with a maverick flair that invigorates rockers like \"[[Suffragette City]]\", \"Moonage Daydream\" and \"Hang On to Yourself\".\"<ref name=\"Erlewine AllMusic\">{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-rise-and-all-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-mw0000626129 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310010804/https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-rise-and-all-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-mw0000626129 |archivedate=10 March 2020}}</ref> Ned Raggett, also of AllMusic, calls the track one of Bowie's \"fiercest rockers ever\".<ref name=\"AllMusic Raggett\" /> He continues, \"As a prototype of glam rock's still-influential formula \u2013 descending, slow chords; high singing; sexually charged if not exploded imagery; thick, fat feedback; and more \u2013it nails it on every level.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic Raggett\" /> He finishes his review writing: \"Ronson's keyboards and final, swirling string arrangement, matched with a brilliant guitar solo, prove the icing on the cake, sealing \"Moonage Daydream\" forever as a rock classic.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic Raggett\">{{cite web |last1=Raggett |first1=Ned |title=\"Moonage Daydream\" \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/moonage-daydream-mt0044072047 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704103837/https://www.allmusic.com/song/moonage-daydream-mt0044072047 |archive-date=4 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Ultimate Classic Rock'', in their list of Bowie's ten best songs, listed \"Moonage Daydream\" at number three, calling it one of the most powerful songs on the album\u2014and of his career.<ref name=\"UCR best of\" /> They praised the lyrics and Ronson's guitar work, calling it a \"rock'n'roll tour de force.\"<ref name=\"UCR best of\">{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Spencer |title=Top 10 David Bowie songs |url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/top-david-bowie-songs/ |website=[[Ultimate Classic Rock]] |accessdate=25 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231194433/http://ultimateclassicrock.com/top-david-bowie-songs/ |archivedate=31 December 2019 |date=11 January 2016}}</ref> Ian Fortnam of ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'', when ranking every track on the album from worst to best, placed the song at number six, and praised Ronson's guitar work, calling his ending guitar solo \"\u00fcberglamtastic\" and \"to die for.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/every-track-on-david-bowies-ziggy-stardust-ranked-from-worst-to-best | title=Every song on David Bowie's Ziggy Stardust ranked from worst to best | work=Louder | first=Ian | last=Fortnam | date=11 November 2016 | accessdate=26 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826071416/https://www.loudersound.com/features/every-track-on-david-bowies-ziggy-stardust-ranked-from-worst-to-best | archive-date=26 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, ''[[NME]]'' listed the song as Bowie's 11th greatest.<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last1=Barker |first1=Emily |title=David Bowie's 40 greatest songs \u2013 as decided by ''NME'' and friends |url=https://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends-1418012 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=16 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103063248/https://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends-1418012 |archivedate=3 November 2019 |date=8 January 2018}}</ref> Alexis Petridis of ''[[The Guardian]]'' ranked \"Moonage Daydream\" 33rd in her list of Bowie's 50 greatest songs, calling Ronson's guitar solo \"mind-blowing\" and describing it as the best example of \"high-drama rock anthemics\" on ''Ziggy Stardust''.<ref name=\"Petridis Guardian\">{{cite web |last1=Petridis |first1=Alexis |title=David Bowie's 50 greatest songs \u2013 ranked! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/david-bowie-50-greatest-songs-ranked |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322224635/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/david-bowie-50-greatest-songs-ranked |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Tim Wheeler]] of the Northern Irish rock band [[Ash (band)|Ash]], in an interview with ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine, said, \"With Bowie, you're spoilt for choice when it comes to [[Science fiction|sci-fi]]-inspired songs. But 'Moonage Daydream' is my favourite. It's got a great [[Ostinato|riff]] and it sounds really pretty in a weird kind of way, even though the lyrics are quite dark.\"<ref>{{cite journal|first=Tim |last=[[Tim Wheeler|Wheeler]] |title=Sci-fi rocks |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |date=August 2007 |page=117}}</ref>\n\n==Live versions==\nBowie performed \"Moonage Daydream\" throughout 1972\u201373 on the [[Ziggy Stardust Tour]], where he would occasionally introduce it as \"a song written by Ziggy\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}} A live version from the tour, recorded at Santa Monica Civic Auditorium on 20 October 1972, was released on ''[[Live Santa Monica '72]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thornton |first1=Anthony |title=David Bowie \u2013 'Live: Santa Monica '72' review |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews-david-bowie-9770-308284 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=1 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004181122/http://www.nme.com/reviews/david-bowie/9770 |archive-date=4 October 2012}}</ref> It was also performed during the tour's final concert at the [[Hammersmith Odeon]], London on 3 July 1973, where Bowie announced: \"This is the last show we'll ever do.\" This was later understood as the retiring of Ziggy Stardust.{{sfn|Buckley|1999|p=191}} This recording was released on ''[[Ziggy Stardust: The Motion Picture]]'' (1983).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Joe |first1=Viglione |title=''Ziggy Stardust: The Motion Picture'' |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-the-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000691870 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424115511/https://www.allmusic.com/album/ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-the-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000691870 |archive-date=24 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He recorded the song for the [[BBC]] radio programme ''[[Sounds of the Seventies|Sounds of the 70s]]: [[John Peel]]'' on 16 May 1972. This recording was later released on the album ''[[Bowie at the Beeb]]'' in 2000.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Bowie at the Beeb: The Best of the BBC Radio Sessions 68\u201372'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/bowie-at-the-beeb-the-best-of-the-bbc-radio-sessions-bonus-disc-mw0000619751 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702122107/https://www.allmusic.com/album/bowie-at-the-beeb-the-best-of-the-bbc-radio-sessions-bonus-disc-mw0000619751 |archive-date=2 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bowie subsequently performed the track on the [[Diamond Dogs Tour]], and on the [[Outside Tour|Outside]], [[Earthling Tour|Earthling]] and [[Heathen Tour|Heathen]] tours.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}} Recordings from the Diamond Dogs Tour have been released on ''[[David Live]]'' (1974) and ''[[Cracked Actor (Live Los Angeles '74)]]'' (2017).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''David Live'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/david-live-mw0000033632 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424115457/https://www.allmusic.com/album/david-live-mw0000033632 |archive-date=24 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Randle |first1=Chris |title=David Bowie: ''Cracked Actor (Live Los Angeles '74)'' |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-cracked-actor-live-los-angeles-74/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=29 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117144718/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-cracked-actor-live-los-angeles-74/ |archive-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A live version from the Outside tour, recorded on 13 December 1995, was released on the \"[[Hallo Spaceboy]]\" single in 1996.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}}\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Arnold Corns' version (without the spoken intro \"Whenever you're ready\") was released as a bonus track on the 1990 [[Rykodisc]] re-release of ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' and on the 2002 reissue of ''Ziggy Stardust''.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Man Who Sold the World|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1990|publisher=[[Rykodisc]]|location=US|type=CD liner notes|id=RCD 10132}}</ref><ref name=\"rkyodisc\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=2002|publisher=[[EMI]]|location=US|type=liner notes|id=72435 39826 2}}</ref> The spoken intro was restored for release on ''Re:Call 1'', part of the ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' compilation, in 2015.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=327}}<ref name=\"five years box set\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Five Years (1969\u20131973)|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=2015|publisher=[[Parlophone]]|location=UK, Europe & US|type=Box set liner notes|id=DBXL 1}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Ziggy Stardust'' recording has since appeared on multiple [[compilation album]]s, including the 1989 box set ''[[Sound + Vision (box set)|Sound + Vision]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Sound + Vision'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/sound-vision-mw0000653974 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508195205/https://www.allmusic.com/album/sound-vision-mw0000653974 |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Best of Bowie'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-bowie-mw0000694821 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401192732/https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-bowie-mw0000694821 |archive-date=1 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Nothing Has Changed]]'' (2014),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Nothing Has Changed'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/nothing-has-changed-mw0002764063 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508195204/https://www.allmusic.com/album/nothing-has-changed-mw0002764063 |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ''[[Legacy (The Very Best of David Bowie)|Legacy]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Legacy'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/legacy-mw0002986167 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508195207/https://www.allmusic.com/album/legacy-mw0002986167 |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ''Ziggy'' recording, along with its parent album, has been remastered multiple times, including in 1990 by [[Rykodisc]],<ref>{{cite web|title=The Rise & Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars [Bonus Tracks]|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/the-rise-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-bonus-tracks-mr0001727546|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002175230/http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/the-rise-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-bonus-tracks-mr0001727546|archivedate=2 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1990|publisher=[[Rykodisc]]|location=US|type=liner notes|id=RCD 10134}}</ref> and in 2012 for its 40th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=2012|publisher=[[EMI]]|location=Europe|type=liner notes|id=5099946361417}}</ref> The 2012 remaster and the 2003 remixes by producer Ken Scott, along with the original Arnold Corns' recording, were included on the box set ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' in 2015.<ref name=\"five years box set\" /> A new mix of the track also appears on the 2002 reissue of ''Ziggy Stardust'', on which, in Cann's words, Ronson's guitar is \"to the fore.\"<ref name=\"rkyodisc\" />{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=255}} This mix was originally featured in a 1998 [[Dunlop Tyres|Dunlop]] television commercial.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}}<ref name=\"Drake Metrotimes\">{{cite web|last=Drake|first=Rossiter|title=The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars: 30th Anniversary Edition|url=https://www.metrotimes.com/city-slang/archives/2002/09/04/the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-30th-anniversary-edition|work=[[Metro Times]]|date=4 September 2002|accessdate=2 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002175230/https://www.metrotimes.com/city-slang/archives/2002/09/04/the-rise-and-fall-of-ziggy-stardust-and-the-spiders-from-mars-30th-anniversary-edition|archivedate=2 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in the 2014 film ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' and on its [[Guardians of the Galaxy: Awesome Mix Vol. 1 (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)|soundtrack]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=329}}<ref name=\"Vulture Guardians\">{{cite web|url=https://vulture.com/2014/08/how-guardians-of-the-galaxy-music-soundtrack-was-chosen.html |title=Director James Gunn on How He Chose the Music in Guardians of the Galaxy |last=Suskind |first=Alex |work=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]] |date=August 8, 2014 |accessdate=September 19, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ShD2pm91?url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/08/how-guardians-of-the-galaxy-music-soundtrack-was-chosen.html |archivedate=September 19, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is heard in the film during the [[Guardians of the Galaxy (2008 team)|Guardians]]' entrance to [[Knowhere]], the headquarters of the [[Collector (comics)|Collector]].<ref name=\"Vulture Guardians\" /> Of all the songs on the soundtrack, \"Moonage Daydream\" was the only song added in post-production.<ref name=\"Vulture Guardians\" /> Director [[James Gunn]] was unsure about using it initially, but ended up choosing it over \"[[Wichita Lineman]]\" by [[Glen Campbell]] and \"[[Mama Told Me Not to Come|Mama Told Me (Not to Come)]]\" by [[Three Dog Night]].<ref name=\"Vulture Guardians\" />\n\n''Moonage Daydream: The Life and Times of Ziggy Stardust'', a book written by Bowie, is named after the song and was published in 2002 by [[Genesis Publications]]. It documents the years 1972\u201373 and is fully illustrated with the photography of [[Mick Rock]]. Bowie met him in 1972 and they formed a working relationship and lasting friendship. Rock was the only photographer authorised to record the two-year career of [[David Bowie#Ziggy Stardust|Ziggy Stardust]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Moonage Daydream: The Life & Times of Ziggy Stardust |url=https://www.amazon.com/Moonage-Daydream-Times-Ziggy-Stardust/dp/0789313502 |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219182607/https://www.amazon.com/Moonage-Daydream-Times-Ziggy-Stardust/dp/0789313502 |archive-date=19 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Genesis Publications \u2013 ''Moonage Daydream'' |url=https://www.genesis-publications.com/book/0904351866/moonage-daydream |publisher=[[Genesis Publications]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216074038/https://www.genesis-publications.com/book/0904351866/moonage-daydream |archive-date=16 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Arnold Corns version\nPersonnel per Kevin Cann and Nicholas Pegg.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=604}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=206\u2013207}}\n* David Bowie{{spaced ndash}} vocals, rhythm guitar, producer\n* Freddie Burretti{{spaced ndash}} vocals (credited)<ref name=\"Rhino\">{{cite web |title=Single Stories: David Bowie, \"Moonage Daydream\" |url=https://www.rhino.com/article/single-stories-david-bowie-moonage-daydream |publisher=Rhino |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=7 May 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310010927/https://www.rhino.com/article/single-stories-david-bowie-moonage-daydream |archivedate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Mark Carr-Pritchard{{spaced ndash}} guitar\n* Peter DeSomogyi{{spaced ndash}} bass\n* Tim Broadbent{{spaced ndash}} drums, tambourine\n{{col-2}}\n;''Ziggy Stardust'' version\nPersonnel per Kevin Cann and Nicholas Pegg.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=328}}{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=252}}\n* David Bowie{{spaced ndash}} lead vocals, acoustic guitar, [[saxophone]], [[pennywhistle]], producer\n* [[Mick Ronson]]{{spaced ndash}} electric guitar, piano, backing vocals, [[string section|string]] arrangements\n* [[Trevor Bolder]]{{spaced ndash}} bass\n* [[Mick Woodmansey|Mick \"Woody\" Woodmansey]]{{spaced ndash}} drums\n* [[Ken Scott]]{{spaced ndash}} producer\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book|last=Buckley |first=David |year=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |isbn=978-1-85227-784-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cann |first=Kevin |year=2010 |title=Any Day Now \u2013 David Bowie: The London Years: 1947\u20131974 |publisher=Adelita |isbn=978-0-95520-177-6 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Doggett |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Doggett |year=2012 |title=The Man Who Sold the World: David Bowie and the 1970s |publisher=[[HarperCollins|HarperCollins Publishers]] |isbn=978-0-06-202466-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |publisher=Titan Books |edition=7th |location=London |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-78565-365-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Perone|first=James|title=The Words and Music of David Bowie|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|date=2007|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C6bz2BFdPawC|isbn=978-0-27-599245-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Spitz |first=Marc |author-link1=Marc Spitz |title=Bowie: A Biography |publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]] |year=2009  |isbn=978-0-307-71699-6|title-link=Bowie: A Biography |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Woodmansey|first=Woody<!--credited name-->|authorlink=Mick Woodmansey|title=Spider from Mars: My Life with Bowie|publisher=St. Martin's Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2P3hCwAAQBAJ|isbn=978-1-25-011762-5|date=2017|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|moonage-daydream}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Ken Scott]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Rock ballads]]\n[[Category:1970s ballads]]\n[[Category:Outer space themed songs]]\n", "name_user": "Zmbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelease and reception:+ source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moonage_Daydream"}
{"title_page": "Rafael Bernal", "text_new": "'''Rafael Bernal''' (28 June 1915 &ndash; 17 September 1972) was a [[Mexican people|Mexican]] [[diplomat]] and [[novelist]], best known for his [[crime novels]], particularly ''[[The Mongolian Conspiracy]]''.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">[http://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-rafael-bernal-20140105,0,2683549.story#ixzz2pHKB16IJ 'The Mongolian Conspiracy' is classic Rafael Bernal noir]</ref>\nBernal wrote a book titled ''M\u00e9xico en Filipinas: estudio de una transculturaci\u00f3n'' about the introduction of Mexican culture to the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\"colmex.mx\">http://biblio-codex.colmex.mx/exlibris/aleph/a21_1/apache_media/H3VVXTA1FMCYMSBNAYA4KE6D8IC3LK.pdf{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> His brother was the renowned anthropologist and archaeologist [[Ignacio Bernal]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bernal, Rafael}}\n[[Category:Mexican male novelists]]\n[[Category:Mexican diplomats]]\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican male writers]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Rafael Bernal''' (28 June 1915 &ndash; 17 September 1972) was a [[Mexican people|Mexican]] [[diplomat]] and [[novelist]], best known for his [[crime novels]], particularly ''[[The Mongolian Conspiracy]]''.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">[http://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-rafael-bernal-20140105,0,2683549.story#ixzz2pHKB16IJ 'The Mongolian Conspiracy' is classic Rafael Bernal noir]</ref>\nBernal wrote a book titled ''M\u00e9xico en Filipinas: estudio de una transculturaci\u00f3n'' about the introduction of Mexican culture to the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\"colmex.mx\">http://biblio-codex.colmex.mx/exlibris/aleph/a21_1/apache_media/H3VVXTA1FMCYMSBNAYA4KE6D8IC3LK.pdf{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</r